Date: 0/0/1945
Source: NZ Geographer
Author:
Vol / Page: 19
Edition:
Quote: `Crook' might present difficulty, since its use here has no reference to criminal. `Crook' as an adjective signifies `bad', `ill'. Thus we have `crook weather', `feel crook' and `to go crook', which latter means to be rude or lose one's temper.
Notes: (Cumberland)

Date: 0/0/1974
Source: Australian & NZ English [TS]
Author: SYDER & HODGETTS
Vol / Page: 231
Edition:
Quote: Wrong, unsatisfactory, ailing. .in 4;`Look at this, mortar's crumbling, this brickwork's a crook job.' `We struck some crook weather, even the Norwegians complained about the cold.' `He's got a crook back - it's no use asking him to lift any heavy weight while his back's bad.'
Notes:
